{
  "handoff_brief": {
    "recipient": "Shaq",
    "task_context": "Implement tenant isolation for a multi-tenant SaaS system. Tenant context flows from API gateway through all services (synchronous and asynchronous) to ensure no cross-tenant data leakage. Three agents have aligned on the happy path but one critical gap remains around the failure/missing-context scenario — see open_questions.",
    "domain_rules": [
      {
        "rule": "All data access must be scoped to the authenticated tenant. No cross-tenant data leakage is permitted.",
        "testable_assertion": "A query executed in the context of Tenant A returns zero rows belonging to any other tenant, even if the underlying store contains multi-tenant data."
      },
      {
        "rule": "Tenant context is established at the API gateway before any downstream service is invoked.",
        "testable_assertion": "No service method executes without a non-null, validated TenantContext. Any request reaching a service without tenant context is rejected before data access occurs."
      },
      {
        "rule": "Tenant context must be present on all log lines for audit compliance.",
        "testable_assertion": "Given any log entry produced during a tenant-scoped operation, the log line contains the tenant_id field with the correct value."
      }
    ],
    "architecture_guidance": [
      {
        "decision": "TenantContext object injected into each service, populated from JWT claim 'tenant_id'",
        "implementation_note": "Extract tenant_id from the authenticated JWT at the API gateway or middleware layer. Inject TenantContext via DI so all downstream services receive it without manual threading. This covers synchronous HTTP request paths."
      },
      {
        "decision": "Background workers inherit tenant context from the job payload, not from JWT",
        "implementation_note": "When enqueuing async work, serialize the tenant_id into the job/message payload. The worker deserializes it and constructs a TenantContext before processing. This is the async counterpart to the JWT-based flow for HTTP requests."
      },
      {
        "decision": "All data access layers must filter by tenant_id from TenantContext",
        "implementation_note": "Apply tenant scoping at the repository or query layer — not at the controller. This ensures that even if a new endpoint or worker is added, data isolation is enforced structurally rather than by convention."
      }
    ],
    "acceptance_criteria": [
      {
        "criterion": "Tenant-scoped data access",
        "given": "A request authenticated as Tenant A",
        "when": "Any data query is executed",
        "then": "Only Tenant A's data is returned; zero rows from other tenants appear in the result"
      },
      {
        "criterion": "Tenant context propagation — HTTP path",
        "given": "An HTTP request with a valid JWT containing tenant_id claim",
        "when": "The request reaches any downstream service",
        "then": "The service's injected TenantContext contains the correct tenant_id from the JWT"
      },
      {
        "criterion": "Tenant context propagation — async path",
        "given": "A background job enqueued with tenant_id in its payload",
        "when": "The worker picks up and processes the job",
        "then": "The worker's TenantContext is populated with the tenant_id from the payload before any data access occurs"
      },
      {
        "criterion": "Audit-compliant logging",
        "given": "Any operation executing within a tenant context",
        "when": "A log line is emitted",
        "then": "The log line includes the tenant_id field with the correct value"
      },
      {
        "criterion": "Missing tenant context is rejected",
        "given": "A request or job that arrives without a tenant_id",
        "when": "The system attempts to construct TenantContext",
        "then": "The operation is rejected before any data access occurs (exact behavior TBD — see open_questions)"
      }
    ],
    "terminology_alignment": [
      {
        "domain_term": "Tenant context",
        "technical_term": "TenantContext (injected object)",
        "definition": "The runtime representation of which tenant is acting. In HTTP flows, sourced from JWT claim 'tenant_id'. In async flows, sourced from job payload field 'tenant_id'. Used for data scoping, logging, and audit."
      },
      {
        "domain_term": "Cross-tenant data leakage",
        "technical_term": "Missing or incorrect tenant filter on a data query",
        "definition": "Any scenario where Tenant A can observe, modify, or infer the existence of Tenant B's data. The primary technical defense is mandatory tenant_id filtering at the repository layer."
      }
    ],
    "contradictions_resolved": [
      {
        "conflict": "MJ specifies tenant context from JWT (HTTP path) while Pippen specifies tenant context from job payload (async path) — appears to be two different propagation mechanisms",
        "resolution": "Not a contradiction. These are complementary propagation strategies for two different execution contexts: JWT for synchronous HTTP requests, job payload for asynchronous background workers. Both produce the same TenantContext object for downstream consumption."
      }
    ],
    "open_questions": [
      "Bird has not defined what happens when tenant context is missing or invalid. Pippen explicitly flagged this gap — they are treating 'tenant context always present' as a given, but there is no domain rule for the failure case. Shaq needs a decision from Bird: should requests without valid tenant context receive a 401, a 403, or a domain-specific error? Should background jobs without tenant context be dead-lettered, retried, or silently dropped? This is blocking for the guard/rejection logic but NOT blocking for the happy-path implementation — Shaq can build the happy path now and add the rejection behavior once Bird decides.",
      "No explicit guidance on whether tenant_id scoping should use database-level row filtering, schema-per-tenant, or database-per-tenant. The architecture implies row-level filtering (repository-layer scoping) but this has not been stated as a decision. Shaq should default to row-level filtering unless told otherwise."
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 75,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "Happy-path tenant context propagation is well-defined across both HTTP and async flows — all three agents agree",
      "Data isolation requirement is unambiguous — Bird's domain rule is clear and testable",
      "Logging/audit requirement from Pippen is concrete and implementable"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Failure-mode behavior when tenant context is missing/invalid — Bird has not defined this, and Pippen flagged the gap",
      "Data isolation strategy (row-level vs schema vs database) is not explicitly decided"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "Row-level tenant filtering at the repository layer is the intended isolation strategy",
      "Shaq can implement the happy path and guard clauses separately, treating the missing-context behavior as a follow-up decision from Bird",
      "JWT claim name is literally 'tenant_id' — no mapping or transformation needed"
    ]
  }
}

